♪ Getting colder ♪

01:01.144 --> 01:03.981
♪ Sha la, la, la, la ♪

01:04.022 --> 01:07.359
♪ Sha la, la, la ♪

01:07.401 --> 01:09.945
♪ Sha la, la, la, la ♪

01:09.987 --> 01:14.115
♪ Sha la, la, la, la, la ♪

01:21.373 --> 01:24.919
I believe some things to be
true about England, other than

01:24.960 --> 01:28.047
that I know I can always
find friends there.

01:28.087 --> 01:29.374
It's where you can
find some of the best

01:29.381 --> 01:30.591
restaurants in Europe.

01:30.592 --> 01:31.800
It's beautiful.

01:31.842 --> 01:34.762
It's... I don't know...
Sophisticated.

01:34.803 --> 01:35.888
They're old.

01:35.889 --> 01:36.972
They've been around.

01:37.014 --> 01:40.746
But on this last trip,
unexpectedly, the mood in London

01:40.747 --> 01:44.145
became darker, more
uncertain about the future.

01:44.187 --> 01:46.147
The British people
spoke last night.

01:46.189 --> 01:47.295
Brutal wake-up call.

01:47.296 --> 01:50.151
It turns out that it
was about immigration,

01:50.193 --> 01:52.529
that more than half of
Britain's immigration

01:52.571 --> 01:53.948
comes from outside the EU.

01:53.989 --> 01:55.156
It's a disaster, a calamity.

01:55.198 --> 01:57.639
The young are very, very
angry about what's happened

01:57.640 --> 02:01.204
and the gamble that's being
taken with their future.

02:02.497 --> 02:06.585
Few in London, anyway, went to
sleep thinking that England

02:06.586 --> 02:07.962
would leave the European Union.

02:08.002 --> 02:10.213
That was for the rubes, the
people from the sticks,

02:10.255 --> 02:12.758
the country people,
old, white people,

02:12.800 --> 02:17.429
people who felt pushed out,
neglected, disenfranchised

02:17.430 --> 02:19.557
by the new, the young, the
foreign, the decidedly

02:19.558 --> 02:21.642
less-white England of today.

02:21.683 --> 02:24.311
The votes were tallied,
and the majority

02:24.312 --> 02:25.604
had decided to Brexit.

02:25.646 --> 02:28.189
♪ And the RAF of England ♪

02:28.231 --> 02:31.151
The ramifications were unclear,
but the financial markets

02:31.152 --> 02:34.696
plummeted, the nation's
credit rating was downgraded,

02:34.738 --> 02:38.575
the prime minister resigned,
and both political parties'

02:38.576 --> 02:41.870
leadership basically
disintegrated overnight.

02:47.250 --> 02:49.795
♪

02:49.837 --> 02:52.798
In uncertain times, I always
look for the comforting

02:52.840 --> 02:55.884
and the familiar, the
things that always, for me,

02:55.926 --> 02:58.658
made England great,
like one of my favorite

02:58.659 --> 03:01.307
restaurants on Earth,
and one of the chefs

03:01.308 --> 03:02.516
I like and respect most.

03:02.557 --> 03:06.227
This restaurant helped
make a persuasive argument

03:06.269 --> 03:09.981
that there is some kind of
merit -to British cooking.

03:09.982 --> 03:11.733
Yes.

03:11.775 --> 03:13.234
It's absolutely true.

03:13.276 --> 03:16.113
Fergus Henderson, the
most influential chef

03:16.155 --> 03:18.886
of the last two decades,
even though you have likely

03:18.887 --> 03:20.241
never heard of him.

03:20.283 --> 03:22.243
He changed everything.

03:22.285 --> 03:24.622
It seems an instinctive
thing to cook old-school,

03:24.623 --> 03:27.248
simple, proud, English
country cooking.

03:27.290 --> 03:30.169
But it started a
quiet revolution.

03:31.586 --> 03:36.257
St. John, I love you and I
need you now more than ever.

03:36.299 --> 03:38.259
It's about the single
ingredient on the plate,

03:38.301 --> 03:41.262
speaking for itself in that
classic Italian sort of way.

03:41.304 --> 03:43.431
And so you can get lost.

03:43.473 --> 03:46.727
Roast bone marrow with
parsley and caper salad,

03:46.768 --> 03:48.311
sourdough bread made here.

03:48.353 --> 03:51.481
A dish that would become
absolutely iconic.

03:51.523 --> 03:54.109
If you've ever eaten
bone marrow anywhere,

03:54.151 --> 03:57.278
it's very likely because
they did it here first.

03:57.320 --> 04:01.075
My dinner companion is food
critic and author Jay Rayner,

04:01.116 --> 04:03.785
a man never with a
shortage of opinions.

04:03.827 --> 04:05.704
Bones.

04:05.705 --> 04:07.581
Thank you, yes.

04:07.622 --> 04:09.290
Salt.

04:09.332 --> 04:12.211
And there you go It's
a simple, good thing,

04:12.252 --> 04:14.171
but it's one of the most
influential dishes,

04:14.213 --> 04:15.714
like, in the last 20 years.

04:15.756 --> 04:16.882
It's a good thing.

04:16.923 --> 04:19.551
You see his imprint everywhere.

04:19.593 --> 04:20.281
It's true.

04:20.281 --> 04:22.763
And what's interesting
is that the aesthetic

04:21.011 --> 04:24.681
gets passed down in other
ways that you don't expect.

04:24.723 --> 04:26.183
Yeah.

04:26.225 --> 04:27.809
As I've become
older, I've noticed

04:27.851 --> 04:31.333
the food that I yearn for
is food that I react to

04:31.334 --> 04:33.314
in an entirely emotional way.

04:33.356 --> 04:36.610
The problem is that it's
so very, very rare.

04:36.651 --> 04:41.280
I'm looking for a suspension...
No-

04:41.281 --> 04:43.324
-...of logic and reason.

04:43.366 --> 04:47.746
This is something that I got
here from the beginning.

04:47.788 --> 04:50.395
Pickled calves tripe with
radish, shaved carrot,

04:50.396 --> 04:51.541
and watercress.

04:51.583 --> 04:52.105
Lovely.

04:52.106 --> 04:52.626
Wow.

04:52.667 --> 04:53.398
Wow.

04:53.399 --> 04:54.128
Thank you.

04:54.169 --> 04:55.538
There are some tripe
dishes that are just

04:55.545 --> 04:56.755
uniquely wonderful.

04:56.756 --> 04:57.965
And it's a tricky ingredient.

04:58.006 --> 05:00.341
Once you're cooking it,
it smells like wet dog.

05:00.383 --> 05:02.928
The way we smell things and
taste them is very different.

05:02.970 --> 05:04.096
All the best foods stink.

05:04.097 --> 05:05.222
Yeah.

05:05.264 --> 05:07.057
And it's an extraordinary thing.

05:07.099 --> 05:10.351
These foods, there's a faint
whiff of death about them,

05:10.393 --> 05:12.854
are the ones that remind you
that you're the most alive.

05:12.896 --> 05:15.023
The scent of your own mortality.

05:15.065 --> 05:16.357
Of your own mortality.

05:17.859 --> 05:21.029
Skate poached in court bouillon,
with fennel in green sauce

05:21.071 --> 05:23.364
of fresh parsley,
herbs, and anchovies.

05:23.406 --> 05:24.428
Hmm.

05:24.429 --> 05:25.450
It's nice.

05:27.786 --> 05:30.476
Savory treats -in
the form of kidney.

05:30.477 --> 05:31.748
Oh, the little kidneys.

05:31.790 --> 05:33.374
They're so pretty.

05:33.416 --> 05:35.669
And how were these
kidneys done, sir?

05:35.710 --> 05:38.839
Well, seasoned fair... Nice.

05:38.880 --> 05:43.260
And then put sauce...
P'shh, p'shh!

05:43.302 --> 05:44.970
Sizzling.

05:45.012 --> 05:48.849
Chicken stock...
Butter, p'shh, p'shh.

05:48.890 --> 05:51.977
P'shh, shh, and toast.

05:52.019 --> 05:53.687
Done.

05:53.728 --> 05:54.855
Yes, thank you.

05:54.896 --> 05:56.190
Good, wow.

05:56.231 --> 05:57.315
Eat well.

05:57.316 --> 05:58.399
Thank you.

06:06.449 --> 06:08.994
Pig's head and potato pie.

06:09.036 --> 06:11.913
The head brined, slowly
simmered until tender,

06:11.955 --> 06:15.146
stripped away from the bone,
and seasoned then baked

06:15.147 --> 06:16.835
in pastry with potatoes.

06:16.877 --> 06:18.795
Yes, please.

06:18.837 --> 06:21.131
A traditional dish
that exemplifies

06:21.173 --> 06:22.841
everything I believe in.

06:22.883 --> 06:23.654
Wow.

06:23.655 --> 06:24.425
Nice.

06:24.467 --> 06:25.447
Thank you, sir.

06:25.448 --> 06:26.427
Thank you.

06:26.469 --> 06:27.971
All right.

06:29.931 --> 06:31.266
Oh, look at that.

06:31.308 --> 06:32.371
Great joy.

06:32.372 --> 06:33.434
That's working.

06:33.476 --> 06:35.145
Is this a hot water pastry?

06:35.187 --> 06:38.169
So, it's a puff pastry, but
somehow transfers of fats

06:38.170 --> 06:40.963
through the pig's head out
and the [indistinct] in

06:40.964 --> 06:43.465
makes it so the crust...
It's gorgeous.

06:43.466 --> 06:44.445
Indeed.

06:44.487 --> 06:45.697
Oh, God, that's good.

06:45.739 --> 06:47.032
Extraordinary.

06:47.074 --> 06:49.868
You look at this pie, and it's
almost like something out

06:48.742 --> 06:49.868
of a children's book.

06:49.910 --> 06:50.702
Right.

06:50.703 --> 06:52.913
The pie tradition is
something very, very special.

06:52.954 --> 06:55.040
If you go back in history
to the Hogarth painting,

06:55.082 --> 06:57.271
"The Roast Beef of Old England"...
Yup.

06:57.272 --> 06:59.460
...you'll realize that
actually we were far ahead

06:59.461 --> 07:01.963
of the French in the
preparation of beef

06:59.502 --> 07:01.963
and the roasting of meats.

07:02.005 --> 07:04.258
A lot of it was over our
side of the channel.

07:04.299 --> 07:05.383
Yeah.

07:05.384 --> 07:08.345
Which is no reason for
leaving the European Union.

07:09.763 --> 07:13.141
So they call it Great Britain.

07:13.183 --> 07:14.935
What's great about Britain?

07:14.976 --> 07:20.148
I can refer to a certain literacy
and a wry sense of humor,

07:20.190 --> 07:24.152
and a political tradition of
democracy, which, ironically,

07:24.153 --> 07:27.530
the referendum that's caused
so many of us so much pain

07:27.572 --> 07:29.074
is a perfect example of.

07:29.116 --> 07:32.493
Also, a weirdly cosmopolitan,
welcoming environment

07:32.535 --> 07:36.748
in which the history of
immigration into the country

07:36.790 --> 07:39.126
has defined a far
more open culture.

07:39.167 --> 07:42.921
Until this point I was very,
very proud, but that...

07:42.922 --> 07:43.671
I wouldn't be here.

07:43.713 --> 07:44.791
You know, my great-great
grandparents

07:44.798 --> 07:47.217
arrived as shtetl Jews off
the boat into the East End

07:47.218 --> 07:49.510
of London, and here I
am still to this day,

07:49.552 --> 07:51.512
and that's a very,
very important thing.

07:51.554 --> 07:53.223
A very tolerant country.

07:53.265 --> 07:54.933
This is a very traumatic moment.

07:54.975 --> 07:56.768
Will it all work out in the end?

07:56.810 --> 07:57.894
I have no idea.

07:57.936 --> 07:59.055
- Wow.
- It's the honest truth.

07:59.062 --> 08:01.522
Nothing is certain.

08:01.564 --> 08:03.942
♪

08:05.568 --> 08:08.447
You know what I like?
A good pub.

08:08.488 --> 08:11.158
Like the Princess
Victoria in West London,

08:11.199 --> 08:13.160
and stuff like this.

08:13.201 --> 08:14.744
Did you like pork scratchings?

08:14.786 --> 08:16.788
I do.

08:16.830 --> 08:18.581
Hmm. Cheers.

08:18.623 --> 08:19.585
Oh, that's insanely good.

08:19.624 --> 08:22.543
Maybe you wouldn't think that
the legendary cookbook author

08:22.585 --> 08:25.610
Nigella Lawson and I could
be friends, but we are.

08:25.611 --> 08:28.133
We are, admittedly,
very different.

08:28.175 --> 08:31.386
She is the very definition of
kindness, elegance, grace,

08:31.428 --> 08:33.554
the woman who taught
England to cook.

08:33.596 --> 08:34.554
Nice.

08:34.597 --> 08:36.015
What do you get here ordinarily?

08:36.057 --> 08:36.725
Scotch egg.

08:36.726 --> 08:37.392
All right.

08:37.433 --> 08:39.769
Scotch eggs, please,
and some whitebait.

08:39.811 --> 08:40.645
Certainly.

08:40.647 --> 08:41.480
And some chips.

08:41.520 --> 08:43.475
Whitebait? This is, like, the
greatest thing ever. Really?

08:43.482 --> 08:45.233
Oh, yeah. Whitebait
is so good, isn't it?

08:45.275 --> 08:46.943
In a little pub, you
can get whitebait?

08:46.985 --> 08:50.468
Well, I'm sure in Charles
Dickens' time, they used to have

08:50.469 --> 08:51.281
whitebait then.

08:51.323 --> 08:53.574
Mind you, then, they used
to have oysters too, so...

08:53.616 --> 08:55.160
I can't hear you
over the crunching.

08:55.202 --> 08:56.696
I can't hear myself over
the crunch, actually.

08:56.703 --> 08:59.664
I'll be... I lost interest
in what I was saying.

08:59.706 --> 09:03.460
Whitebait, tiny baby herring
lightly battered whole

09:03.461 --> 09:05.004
and fried, tossed
with a little bit

09:05.005 --> 09:08.673
of lemon juice and salt,
the perfect bar food.

09:08.715 --> 09:10.091
There's this
slightly crisp, huh?

09:10.133 --> 09:10.842
Hmm.

09:10.884 --> 09:12.302
Do you have this in the States?

09:12.344 --> 09:14.179
You're starting to see
them, but almost never.

09:14.221 --> 09:15.638
Beautiful, though, aren't they?

09:15.680 --> 09:17.598
And fat chips, always important.

09:17.640 --> 09:19.600
What is the appropriate
condiment with chips?

09:19.642 --> 09:22.603
Being old-fashioned, I
think vinegar and salt.

09:22.645 --> 09:25.524
If I'm in Brussels or Holland,
I'm fine about mayonnaise,

09:25.565 --> 09:26.934
- but if it's here...
- Oh [indistinct] there,

09:26.941 --> 09:28.276
- I'm with you there.
- Yeah.

09:28.318 --> 09:30.404
And what is it, chips
with curry sauce?

09:30.445 --> 09:32.447
Hmm, fantastic. Sorry.

09:32.489 --> 09:35.909
It's really a matter of how
many Guinnesses you've had.

09:35.950 --> 09:38.619
A soft-boiled egg, wrap
it in minced pork,

09:38.661 --> 09:41.622
then roll it in bread crumbs, and what?
Deep-fry it?

09:41.664 --> 09:45.710
It's like a supernova of
unhealthiness and deliciousness.

09:45.752 --> 09:48.255
This is the important thing,
the softness of the yolk.

09:48.296 --> 09:49.630
Right. Who invented this?

09:49.672 --> 09:51.007
It's just fiendish.

09:51.049 --> 09:52.877
One of the explanations,
Scotch used to preserve eggs

09:52.884 --> 09:54.344
and send them to England.

09:54.386 --> 09:56.172
What would happen is that
they would [indistinct]

09:56.179 --> 09:59.349
Some sort of lime on them,
and it would discolor them,

09:59.391 --> 10:01.518
so they then covered
them to hide that.

10:01.560 --> 10:03.311
This is just right.

10:03.353 --> 10:07.065
When I grew up, they were
very low-rent, very cheap,

10:07.066 --> 10:09.943
rather spooky sausage
meat, rock-hard egg,

10:09.984 --> 10:12.863
that sort of tinge like,
you know, -Uranus.

10:12.864 --> 10:13.364
Right.

10:13.405 --> 10:15.741
Uranus, as they prefer to
call it now because they get

10:15.742 --> 10:16.533
embarrassed.

10:16.575 --> 10:19.119
And then deep-fried into those
cheap red bread crumbs.

10:19.160 --> 10:20.912
And then it got rehabilitated.

10:20.954 --> 10:23.123
Very good eggs, very
good pork meat.

10:23.164 --> 10:24.665
All your basic food groups.

10:24.707 --> 10:25.785
- Hmm.
- These are really good.

10:25.792 --> 10:26.918
Hmm, really good.

10:26.960 --> 10:29.379
Salt and fat, nothing better.

10:29.421 --> 10:31.089
Oh, yeah.

10:32.591 --> 10:33.592
This is nice.

10:33.633 --> 10:34.926
It is nice, strangely calm.

10:34.968 --> 10:37.596
It is an argument from England.

10:37.637 --> 10:38.158
Really?

10:38.159 --> 10:38.679
Yeah.

10:38.721 --> 10:40.681
- If you have a good pub...
- Yes.

10:40.723 --> 10:42.517
...and if you're
gonna have a pint,

10:42.559 --> 10:43.511
this is the perfect time.

10:43.518 --> 10:44.602
It's quiet.

10:44.603 --> 10:45.686
It is.

10:45.728 --> 10:48.689
We can pretend all is
right with the universe.

10:48.731 --> 10:49.774
I'm going to pretend.

