found out to their
dismay, ain't London.

11:05.915 --> 11:09.231
It's different out
there and a lot of it

11:09.232 --> 11:11.087
is very, very beautiful.

11:11.129 --> 11:13.756
As we get older, we
start to look backwards

11:13.798 --> 11:16.384
in our life and reflect.

11:16.426 --> 11:18.719
When we're young, we
only look forward,

11:18.761 --> 11:19.929
we don't think of our past.

11:19.971 --> 11:23.141
Our past has such a small value.

11:24.476 --> 11:26.811
I'm of an age now,
we become nostalgic,

11:26.853 --> 11:30.357
we become philosophical.

11:30.398 --> 11:33.589
One can, if a successful gentleman
of many accomplishments,

11:33.590 --> 11:36.737
for instance, with a little
bit of money to spend,

11:36.779 --> 11:39.595
make, as Emerson
advised, your own world

11:39.596 --> 11:40.908
far from the madness.

11:40.950 --> 11:45.746
We're in North Wiltshire, and
there's Bath in the distance.

11:45.788 --> 11:47.123
It's really beautiful.

11:47.165 --> 11:49.543
Oh, yeah, nice view.

11:49.584 --> 11:53.129
You'll see how it
just drifts away.

11:53.171 --> 11:55.756
So that's about five
miles as the crow flies.

11:55.798 --> 11:59.469
There are few chefs who set
the world of chefs aflame

11:59.511 --> 12:00.761
like Marco Pierre White.

12:00.803 --> 12:03.473
As young cooks, looking
at his incredible rise

12:03.515 --> 12:05.684
from working-class
boy to the youngest

12:05.685 --> 12:08.936
three-Michelin-starred chef in
the world, we were inspired,

12:08.978 --> 12:11.481
not just by his
accomplishments and his food,

12:11.523 --> 12:14.296
which were amazing, no
great chef had ever

12:14.297 --> 12:17.028
looked like him before
or talked like him.

12:17.070 --> 12:19.573
We were not, it appeared, alone.

12:19.614 --> 12:22.867
I want to turn Rudloe into a house...
Uhhmm.

12:22.868 --> 12:26.871
...not a hotel, so when you
walk inside, it's personal.

12:26.913 --> 12:28.789
Once obsessed with
nothing but working

12:28.831 --> 12:31.522
the hardest, the
longest, being the best,

12:31.523 --> 12:33.878
Marco has transferred
his obsessive nature

12:33.920 --> 12:37.173
to the more pleasurable task
of making the Rudloe Arms

12:37.174 --> 12:38.883
his perfect place.

12:38.925 --> 12:41.802
What's important
about a restaurant

12:41.844 --> 12:44.723
is the feel, not a look.

12:44.763 --> 12:47.726
You could go to the best
restaurant in the world tomorrow.

12:47.766 --> 12:48.928
They could serve the best food.

12:48.935 --> 12:51.812
But if you don't feel comfortable
within that environment,

12:51.854 --> 12:53.314
you'll never enjoy it.

12:53.356 --> 12:58.528
Inside is as much a project
as the grounds, every detail.

12:58.570 --> 13:01.656
Then you can be yourself.

13:01.698 --> 13:03.324
Number one, environment.

13:03.366 --> 13:04.825
Number two, service.

13:04.867 --> 13:06.369
Number three, food.

13:08.162 --> 13:12.125
A pan-roasted filet of
beef with escargot.

13:12.166 --> 13:15.336
Whoa. It's beautiful.

13:15.378 --> 13:16.837
Who do you want to come here?

13:16.879 --> 13:18.715
People who enjoy themselves.

13:18.757 --> 13:19.840
I like a mixed demographic.

13:19.882 --> 13:21.301
- I wanna have everybody.
- Uh-hmm.

13:21.342 --> 13:23.844
I don't want to just
target one market.

13:23.886 --> 13:25.930
Food should be affordable.

13:28.767 --> 13:30.101
Very, very good.

13:30.143 --> 13:33.730
Has your food always reflected
your aspirations and dreams

13:33.772 --> 13:35.148
rather than where you came from?

13:35.189 --> 13:38.234
I was born and bred on the
outskirts of Leeds in a project

13:38.235 --> 13:38.859
housing estate.

13:38.901 --> 13:41.780
Even though I was born into
very humble beginnings,

13:41.820 --> 13:44.865
I used to cross my road,
walk over the golf course,

13:44.907 --> 13:47.744
and there I was on the
Harewood Estates,

13:47.786 --> 13:51.018
designed by the great Capability
Brown, the stately home

13:51.019 --> 13:52.123
of the Earl of Harewood.

13:52.165 --> 13:54.083
That was my playground.

13:55.585 --> 13:58.505
I was fascinated by
the countryside.

13:58.546 --> 14:01.362
I loved the rivers, the
streams, the brooks,

14:01.363 --> 14:02.300
the fields, the woods.

14:02.342 --> 14:06.721
What was within them,
that's what captured me.

14:06.763 --> 14:08.765
It was a dream.

14:08.807 --> 14:11.892
That was my escapism.

14:11.934 --> 14:13.186
My mother died when I was six.

14:13.227 --> 14:16.731
Mother Nature, she became
my surrogate mother.

14:16.773 --> 14:18.899
And so, therefore, I
have this amazing

14:18.941 --> 14:22.320
love affair with nature.

14:22.362 --> 14:24.322
But look, once you go into
a high-end restaurant,

14:24.364 --> 14:27.429
you're about as far as
from nature as you can be.

14:27.430 --> 14:29.910
I mean, it's hard to
rise up the ranks

14:29.952 --> 14:32.914
of a good fine-dining restaurant,
particularly in the time

14:32.915 --> 14:34.499
that you came up.

14:34.541 --> 14:35.916
Shit was not easy.

14:35.958 --> 14:40.401
Everybody in the kitchen
that I started in came from

14:40.402 --> 14:41.840
a housing project.

14:41.881 --> 14:42.923
They were working-class.

14:42.965 --> 14:43.924
They were tough.

14:43.966 --> 14:46.010
They were hard, really hard.

14:46.052 --> 14:48.429
The flip side of that coin...

14:50.598 --> 14:52.058
was nature.

14:53.267 --> 14:57.480
It was all those beautiful
ingredients, that beautiful

14:57.481 --> 14:58.981
contradiction.

15:03.027 --> 15:05.238
Come see my family.

15:07.574 --> 15:10.034
Piggies! Come on,
piggy, piggy, piggies.

15:10.076 --> 15:11.411
Holy crap.

15:11.412 --> 15:12.746
Come on, piggies!

15:12.787 --> 15:13.954
Piggies! What do you think?

15:15.164 --> 15:16.283
They seemed very well-groomed.

15:16.290 --> 15:17.958
They're beautiful.

15:18.000 --> 15:19.370
Don't eat, that's... those
are jeans, not food.

15:19.377 --> 15:21.337
They give you love
bites, trust me.

15:21.379 --> 15:24.465
Piggies, what do you think about
our friends from America?

15:24.507 --> 15:26.342
- Yeah.
- What breed of pig are these?

15:26.384 --> 15:27.968
These are Oxford
Sandy and Black.

15:28.010 --> 15:29.846
They're a traditional
Wiltshire pig.

15:29.888 --> 15:32.891
In four months, this is
how big they've got.

15:32.932 --> 15:34.851
Wow.

15:34.893 --> 15:36.977
They remember your
voice and your smell.

15:37.019 --> 15:39.063
They're really,
really affectionate.

15:39.105 --> 15:40.981
Naturally, they're woodland.

15:41.023 --> 15:43.067
Indeed, beautiful.

15:43.109 --> 15:44.819
It's almost
self-sustaining here.

15:44.861 --> 15:46.863
Well, we will be for
a bacon [indistinct]

15:48.030 --> 15:49.407
Bye, pigs.

15:49.408 --> 15:50.784
Piggies.

15:50.825 --> 15:52.326
Piggies.

15:53.953 --> 15:55.371
I've never been happier here.

15:55.413 --> 15:58.082
I've found somewhere
I'm really happy.

16:00.460 --> 16:03.233
The legendary classic on
Marco's original menu

16:03.234 --> 16:07.049
back in the day, pig's trotter
a la Pierre Koffmann,

16:07.091 --> 16:10.010
an homage to another
great chef and mentor.

16:10.052 --> 16:12.012
It is perfection.

16:12.054 --> 16:14.599
Oh, my God, that is beautiful.

16:14.641 --> 16:17.539
When I was a young cook, we
would look at photographs

16:17.540 --> 16:20.855
of this dish, my
comrades and colleagues,

16:20.897 --> 16:23.441
and gape at it with wonder.

16:23.483 --> 16:26.026
First we'd say, "Oh, my
God, that's gorgeous,"

16:26.068 --> 16:27.111
and, "How did he do it?"

16:27.153 --> 16:29.029
It just got all of
the textural things

16:29.071 --> 16:31.031
that every great cuisine
around the world

16:31.073 --> 16:33.952
understands to be, "Wow."

16:33.993 --> 16:36.851
Pig's trotter has got 24
bones, so you have to remove

16:36.852 --> 16:37.747
all those bones.

16:37.789 --> 16:39.707
And then you braise
it for four hours.

16:39.749 --> 16:40.896
Right.

16:40.897 --> 16:42.042
It's very simple.

16:42.084 --> 16:44.420
People think it's more
complicated than it is.

16:44.462 --> 16:46.923
I know. This is
tricky... tricky dish.

16:46.965 --> 16:50.760
The hero of the dish,
really, is the skin.

16:50.802 --> 16:52.052
Yes.

16:52.094 --> 16:55.055
It's just one of those
great creations.

16:55.097 --> 16:59.936
As the French say, "We never
grow old around the table."

16:59.978 --> 17:04.106
They also say, "Only the
first bottle is expensive."

17:05.775 --> 17:06.859
Cheers.

17:06.901 --> 17:10.363
♪

17:15.034 --> 17:18.162
So this is my big
project I'm working on

17:18.204 --> 17:20.915
because I've fallen in
love with this little part

17:20.915 --> 17:22.040
of England.

17:24.210 --> 17:27.172
I put myself out to
graze, I suppose,

17:27.173 --> 17:28.381
I'm gonna say I'm retired.

17:28.422 --> 17:31.091
And I like to do what I do here.

17:31.133 --> 17:33.093
If I look at the amount of
nature we have here now,

17:33.135 --> 17:35.013
since we've done what
we've done, it's enormous

17:35.054 --> 17:36.472
- -compared to what we had.
- Right.

17:36.514 --> 17:39.099
And I like seeing the
increase of songbirds,

17:39.141 --> 17:42.729
the hens with their young
chicks, the geese they're my...

17:46.024 --> 17:47.108
Fabulous, aren't they?

17:47.109 --> 17:48.192
Amazing.

17:48.234 --> 17:50.361
They're nuts.

17:50.403 --> 17:52.530
They are beautifully,
beautifully nuts.

17:54.365 --> 17:56.784
There's no guarantees how
long we're gonna be here.

17:56.826 --> 17:59.328
Just enjoy life.

17:59.370 --> 18:02.582
♪

18:05.543 --> 18:10.006
The mood in London is like a
collective nervous breakdown.

18:10.048 --> 18:12.050
Drinking seems appropriate.

18:12.091 --> 18:17.931
But first, a proper base must
be established, some food.

18:17.972 --> 18:19.139
All right.

18:19.181 --> 18:20.934
You have saltfish
callaloo, right?

18:20.975 --> 18:21.684
Yeah.

18:21.685 --> 18:23.770
I'll have some of that
and then vegetable patty.

18:23.811 --> 18:25.730
Saltfish, I think I'll
have one of those.

18:25.772 --> 18:27.189
And the mutton would be good.

18:27.231 --> 18:29.149
This is what happens
when I come off tour.

18:29.191 --> 18:31.945
Straight here, stuff my
face, then half a Guinness,

18:31.986 --> 18:33.738
and then the night is
good, so, you know.

18:33.780 --> 18:36.491
Jamie Hince is half the
creative alliance that makes up

18:36.492 --> 18:37.617
the band The Kills.

18:37.658 --> 18:41.788
Maybe you know them from
such shows as... this one.

18:41.829 --> 18:44.373
And this, Peppers and
Spice in Islington,

18:44.415 --> 18:47.334
is his favorite local
joint for Caribbean food.

18:47.376 --> 18:49.169
I'm enjoying your
currency lately.

18:49.211 --> 18:51.082
It's suddenly become very
affordable since yesterday.

18:51.089 --> 18:52.172
You know, I know.

18:52.214 --> 18:53.830
You know, Britain, we've
got a long history

18:53.841 --> 18:57.157
of taking back control of our
country, you know, getting

18:57.158 --> 18:58.178
in the driving seat again.

18:58.220 --> 19:00.890
And then we get in there and
we just let the handbrake off,

19:00.932 --> 19:02.182
and that's it, you know?

19:02.224 --> 19:03.559
Thank you so much.

19:03.601 --> 19:04.644
I'm extremely hungry.

19:04.685 --> 19:06.104
I'm very excited about this.

19:06.145 --> 19:07.772
Yeah, everything's good.

19:07.814 --> 19:10.066
The best Jamaican this
side of Ocho Rios.

19:10.108 --> 19:11.150
Damn, that's tasty.

19:11.151 --> 19:13.694
I've spent so much time
hanging out with people

19:13.695 --> 19:15.655
where you just eat really
posh, gourmet food,

19:15.696 --> 19:18.198
and when I come off tour, I
just get... start salivating

19:18.240 --> 19:19.346
when I'm on Essex Road.

19:19.347 --> 19:20.451
Uh-hmm.

19:20.493 --> 19:22.996
It is a shame they don't
have a bar here, though.

19:23.037 --> 19:24.204
Right.

19:24.246 --> 19:25.915
You have to drink
a lot, don't you?

19:25.957 --> 19:28.501
I know, it's... -In my job as well...
...hard out.

19:28.542 --> 19:31.587
...people don't think
about that, you know?

19:31.629 --> 19:33.402
How much I have to drink
just to do this.

19:33.403 --> 19:34.132
Bastards.

19:34.173 --> 19:36.926
I mean, they should be
more sensitive to that.

19:36.968 --> 19:37.927
They should be.

19:37.969 --> 19:41.097
♪

19:41.139 --> 19:44.224
It's been one of the nastiest
campaigns, so much lying,

19:44.266 --> 19:45.080
so much dissembling.

19:45.081 --> 19:45.893
Catastrophe.

19:45.935 --> 19:49.105
So far, the reaction
has been, well, chaos.

19:49.147 --> 19:51.858
So, yesterday, prime
minister resigned.

19:51.899 --> 19:53.484
England leaving the
European Union.

19:53.526 --> 19:57.904
Honestly, it kind of makes me feel like...
I don't believe

19:57.905 --> 20:00.324
in democracy anymore.

20:00.366 --> 20:03.661
How quickly the pound is
reacting to political news.

20:03.703 --> 20:06.330
We're entering a very
dark, dangerous period.

20:06.372 --> 20:08.499
Politics where things
are decided by the...

20:08.541 --> 20:11.272
People were talking about, "It's
just dumb having a central"

20:11.273 --> 20:12.252
government in Brussels.

20:12.294 --> 20:14.881
"We've got nothing in common
with people from Romania..."

20:13.462 --> 20:14.881
Right.

20:14.922 --> 20:16.256
"...and Bulgaria."

20:16.298 --> 20:17.960
So, I haven't got anything
in common with people

20:17.967 --> 20:20.616
from Sunderland or Wales, you
know, just like they haven't

20:20.617 --> 20:22.889
got anything in common
with people from London.

20:22.930 --> 20:25.329
When some old people in Great
Yarmouth, get them to decide

20:25.330 --> 20:25.975
the budget.

20:26.017 --> 20:27.935
Give, like, the foreign policy,

20:27.977 --> 20:31.189
get the people from
Sunderland to decide that.

20:32.356 --> 20:34.441
London's a lot different from
the rest of the country.

20:34.483 --> 20:35.777
Right.

20:35.778 --> 20:37.070
It's wealthier, for a start.

20:37.111 --> 20:38.946
It's way more cosmopolitan.

20:38.988 --> 20:40.698
And people complain
about it all the time,

20:40.740 --> 20:43.534
between the people that are
struggling and the people

20:42.116 --> 20:43.534
that are doing well.

20:43.576 --> 20:46.099
What it really shone a
light on is how divided

20:46.100 --> 20:47.287
the country is.

20:47.329 --> 20:49.289
People don't just look at
it as a financial thing.

20:49.331 --> 20:51.125
It's an issue of
cultural identity too.

20:51.167 --> 20:53.461
Citizens who have lived
here for 10, 15 years,

20:53.462 --> 20:56.547
for the first time ever, being
the victims of racial abuse.

20:56.589 --> 20:58.132
Are you evil?

20:58.174 --> 21:00.134
British drinking patterns
seem to be driven

21:00.176 --> 21:02.887
by the fact that pubs
close at, what, midnight.

21:02.929 --> 21:03.763
Yeah.

21:03.764 --> 21:07.371
I noticed, as we approach
last call, people start, like,

21:07.372 --> 21:08.559
doubling up.

21:08.601 --> 21:11.520
The drinking starts to
accelerate in a mad panic.

21:11.562 --> 21:14.356
Load as many in.

21:14.398 --> 21:16.316
Do you think if you extend
the drinking hours,

21:16.358 --> 21:18.903
that it would improve
behavior or make it worse?

21:18.945 --> 21:20.320
I mean, let's face it.

21:20.362 --> 21:22.573
Your countrymen have a bad
reputation as far as...

21:22.615 --> 21:23.178
Drinking.

21:23.179 --> 21:25.034
...sensible... yeah,
sensible drinking.

21:25.076 --> 21:28.996
Do you think that's a function of...
Whatever.

21:33.375 --> 21:36.587
♪

21:38.380 --> 21:42.760
You know, when I was 14,
15, "Fear and Loathing"

21:42.761 --> 21:44.220
came out in Rolling Stone.

21:44.262 --> 21:46.346
I think it was the artwork first

21:46.388 --> 21:50.559
that spoke to me in a
really transformative way.

21:50.601 --> 21:54.354
♪

21:54.396 --> 21:57.817
It captured perfectly all of
my rage, all of the absurdity,

21:57.858 --> 21:59.359
all of these things
that I didn't think

21:59.401 --> 22:01.403
anybody else was seeing or responding to...
Yeah.

22:01.404 --> 22:02.362
...in the same way.

22:02.404 --> 22:04.991
It was unlike anything I'd seen.

22:05.032 --> 22:09.891
Artist, author, icon, Ralph
Steadman, continues to make art

22:09.892 --> 22:11.371
every day.

22:11.413 --> 22:14.271
He was the visual expression of Dr.
Hunter S. Thompson's

22:14.272 --> 22:15.417
finest works.

22:15.459 --> 22:18.711
When Hunter came, 1991,
1992, I brought him

22:18.712 --> 22:20.173
down to the pub here.

22:20.214 --> 22:22.196
"Oh, Martin, this is Hunter."

22:22.197 --> 22:24.177
"Hello."

22:24.218 --> 22:28.222
Here would be Ralph's local,
The Chequers Inn in Kent.

22:28.264 --> 22:29.556
"Hunter, what do you like?"

22:29.598 --> 22:30.891
"Chivas Regal, please."

22:30.933 --> 22:34.312
So I said, "Okay, Martin,
could you make [indistinct]"

22:34.313 --> 22:35.313
That a double?"

22:35.353 --> 22:38.398
Well, these optics, you know,
they've got nothing in them.

22:38.440 --> 22:40.776
They're tiny, little
chiclet-size, yeah.

22:40.818 --> 22:44.864
So did that twice with it, put
it down in front of Hunter.

22:44.905 --> 22:48.366
Hunter looked at it and he
said, "What's that, a sample?"

22:52.913 --> 22:54.414
Where are you from originally?

22:54.456 --> 22:55.415
Well, I am Welsh.

22:55.457 --> 23:00.587
My mother, she was Gwenny
Rogers from Rhosllanerchrugog.

23:00.629 --> 23:02.422
Uh-huh, don't ask
me to spell that.

23:02.464 --> 23:04.675
No, I can't even do it myself.

23:04.717 --> 23:07.303
So how English do you feel,
given that you grew up

23:05.843 --> 23:07.303
in Wales?

23:07.345 --> 23:11.849
Well, in a way, you know, it
was not far from Liverpool.

23:11.891 --> 23:15.186
The food is pub fare, a
runny egg wrapped in

23:15.187 --> 23:19.023
Parma ham and breadcrumbs,
prawn cocktail for the man.

23:19.065 --> 23:21.943
I think, it was the Scanlan's
article the first you worked

23:21.944 --> 23:22.818
with Hunter Thompson?

23:22.860 --> 23:23.799
Kentucky Derby?

23:23.800 --> 23:24.737
Yeah.

23:24.778 --> 23:27.240
Wait, before that, would
you say that you were

23:27.241 --> 23:30.076
a respectable figure, making
a living doing your work?

23:30.117 --> 23:33.975
Because you kind of were
transformed very quickly into a

23:33.976 --> 23:35.539
counter-cultural figure.

23:35.581 --> 23:38.167
I think a lot of people
will, appropriately or not,

23:38.209 --> 23:39.543
see you as an outlaw artist.

23:39.585 --> 23:42.255
Yeah, but I didn't start off
wanting to be an artist.

23:42.296 --> 23:44.840
I wanted to be an
aircraft engineer.

23:44.882 --> 23:47.843
I didn't like factory life,
but I had to go every week

23:47.844 --> 23:50.867
to do technical drawing,
and that's where the lines

23:50.868 --> 23:52.556
and circles began.

23:52.598 --> 23:54.308
Right.

23:54.350 --> 23:57.166
I've been doing a book
called "Critical Critters:"

23:57.167 --> 24:00.773
The Beastly Sneers and Callous
Observations by Ceri Levy."

24:00.814 --> 24:02.108
He's writing about the thing.

24:02.149 --> 24:03.525
Articulated bum lice?

24:03.567 --> 24:05.485
Yeah. Oh, yeah.

24:05.527 --> 24:08.447
I don't know whether
they exist, but... Well,

24:08.448 --> 24:10.490
I'm pretty sure they do...
What?

24:09.115 --> 24:10.490
Yeah, I'm pretty sure they do.

24:10.532 --> 24:11.221
Really?

24:11.222 --> 24:13.493
Some sort... there's
definitely bum-seeking insects

24:13.535 --> 24:15.329
that I've encountered,
they [indistinct]

24:15.371 --> 24:17.331
He thinks that I'm obsessed
with things to do with,

24:17.373 --> 24:19.792
you know, lavatorial humor.

24:19.833 --> 24:21.501
That's kind of an English thing.

24:21.543 --> 24:22.920
Is it?

24:22.962 --> 24:26.027
I saw an advert, "You,
too, can learn to draw"

24:26.028 --> 24:27.507
and earn pounds."

24:27.549 --> 24:30.594
I took the course while I
was doing military service.

24:30.636 --> 24:33.431
I was drawing the guys in
the billet playing cards,

24:33.471 --> 24:35.599
blankets on the bed,
boots in the bed.

24:35.641 --> 24:37.017
Very simplistic stuff.

24:37.059 --> 24:39.145
Nevertheless, it got me started.

24:39.186 --> 24:40.771
And have you heard
of an echidna?

24:40.813 --> 24:42.022
I have not.

24:42.064 --> 24:44.108
This is a hedgehog
type of creature.

24:44.150 --> 24:45.776
There aren't many of
these left, you know.

24:45.818 --> 24:47.320
They reach critical stages.

24:47.361 --> 24:49.905
And this is going in,
too, 'cause, "Excuse me",

24:49.947 --> 24:53.242
we're collecting from
endangered species."

24:56.454 --> 24:58.122
We can all learn
to do this first.

24:58.164 --> 25:00.540
- Not this...
- Right.

25:00.582 --> 25:02.500
But this.

25:03.627 --> 25:05.692
That is very difficult.

25:05.693 --> 25:07.756
I don't think I can do that.

25:07.798 --> 25:09.216
I'm quite sure I can't.

25:09.258 --> 25:11.135
My basic motor skills
are not so good.

25:11.177 --> 25:12.552
Here, you got fish and chips.

25:12.594 --> 25:14.138
Oh, blimey.

25:14.180 --> 25:15.639
More old-school on
the main courses.

25:15.681 --> 25:18.642
Fish and chips with
mushy peas over there,

25:18.684 --> 25:21.979
Steak and Stilton pie for me,
because any mystery meat

25:21.980 --> 25:25.565
wrapped in pastry at a pub
is pure crack for me.

25:25.607 --> 25:26.775
Thank you very much.

25:26.817 --> 25:28.068
Oh, you've got the pie, wow.

25:28.110 --> 25:28.840
Oh, yeah.

25:28.841 --> 25:29.569
Hmm.

25:29.611 --> 25:31.613
We don't do this
back in America.

25:32.823 --> 25:36.035
So many people have said to me,
"Do you pencil it in first?"

25:36.076 --> 25:39.288
I said, "No, you
just start drawing."

25:39.330 --> 25:40.998
"But don't you make a mistake?"

25:41.040 --> 25:43.250
I said, "There's no such
thing as a mistake."

25:43.292 --> 25:46.170
A mistake is an opportunity
to do something else.

25:46.212 --> 25:48.881
You have to leave it and let
nature take its course.

25:48.922 --> 25:51.967
Oh, my God, now,
isn't that lovely?

25:52.009 --> 25:54.594
That is... I like... I'm
impressing myself.

25:54.636 --> 25:55.888
It's so good.

25:55.929 --> 25:58.598
All of nature is
impressing me, actually.

25:58.640 --> 26:01.601
That it's just so
wonderful how it works.

26:01.643 --> 26:06.773
It's a kind of natural process
of evolution, isn't it?

26:06.815 --> 26:10.486
It's what we're
doing all the time.

26:10.528 --> 26:12.279
You're certainly your
depiction of politicians

26:12.321 --> 26:14.865
early on. You seemed filled
with rage and disgust,

26:14.907 --> 26:16.283
deservedly, I'd think.

26:16.325 --> 26:19.203
And there were some epic
depictions of Nixon.

26:19.245 --> 26:21.247
Was it Nixon as Godzilla,
was it, that I...

26:21.288 --> 26:22.915
Yeah, he was a great subject.

26:22.956 --> 26:26.293
I mean, I've done him as a
flying Nixon, a vampire Nixon,

26:26.294 --> 26:28.628
bat Nixon... Did you ever
get an official reaction

26:28.670 --> 26:29.831
to your work from
the White House?

26:29.838 --> 26:30.860
Never.

26:30.861 --> 26:33.342
"I am not a giant,
shitting Godzilla."

26:34.301 --> 26:36.345
You don't wanna deny that.

26:36.387 --> 26:38.931
No, it's funny how that was.

26:38.972 --> 26:40.266
And Boris Johnson here.

26:40.307 --> 26:42.142
I think the hair, in
this case, is just...

26:42.184 --> 26:43.643
It's an irresistible impulse.

26:43.685 --> 26:45.645
Well, to do it, I... I've
got to come out

26:45.687 --> 26:47.147
with it more [indistinct]

26:47.148 --> 26:48.606
But it's perfect.

26:50.943 --> 26:52.445
Boris is our Trump.

26:52.486 --> 26:54.654
Well, they're both...
It is a supernova

26:54.696 --> 26:55.676
of incredibly bad hair.

26:55.677 --> 26:56.656
Yeah.

26:56.698 --> 26:59.889
I mean, the two of them together...
What's happening? What's

26:59.890 --> 27:01.078
going on in this country?

27:01.120 --> 27:02.704
Is it gonna be okay?

27:02.746 --> 27:04.331
Not at the moment, no.

27:04.373 --> 27:06.666
Does it say anything about
the country as a whole?

27:06.708 --> 27:07.876
So, I think it does.

27:07.918 --> 27:10.379
Perhaps there's been a
secret desire to really say,

27:10.380 --> 27:13.507
"Wait a minute, what would
it be like to be on a...

27:13.549 --> 27:15.759
The... a great British
Isles again?"

27:15.801 --> 27:17.761
I was doing this last week just

27:17.762 --> 27:20.722
because I can't stand
snakes, so I said,

27:20.723 --> 27:21.681
"Okay, I'll do you one."

27:21.723 --> 27:26.145
I did one snake last week,
decided to do this,

27:26.186 --> 27:28.606
Saint Lucia racer snake.

27:28.646 --> 27:30.690
Ugh, right there.

27:30.732 --> 27:34.111
And then the next day,
we had the referendum.

27:34.153 --> 27:37.697
Friday morning, when people
realized what had happened,

27:37.739 --> 27:38.949
there was a terrible gloom.

27:38.991 --> 27:40.993
There's a scent I...
We all felt it.

27:41.034 --> 27:43.870
This desire to restore
England to its former glory

27:43.912 --> 27:47.500
as the British Isles, it's
certainly given a revived,

27:47.541 --> 27:51.108
a very powerful urge in Scotland...
to reconsider whether

27:51.109 --> 27:52.630
they wanna be a part.

27:52.670 --> 27:54.798
Oh, dear. I think it's
only gonna get worse

27:54.840 --> 27:56.509
- -before it gets better.
- Uh-hmm.

27:56.550 --> 27:58.969
And I'm certain that what we
are experiencing at the moment

27:59.011 --> 28:02.431
is a kind of rather large
hangover from something

28:02.473 --> 28:07.561
that we've still got to come
to terms with and get over.

28:07.603 --> 28:10.230
Do you think some of your
stuff has anger in there,

28:10.272 --> 28:14.443
or exasperation, or...
That's... I think so... look,

28:14.485 --> 28:18.780
I said to... I don't know,
50 years ago that I wanted

28:18.781 --> 28:23.118
to change the world, and
I think, 50 years later,

28:23.160 --> 28:24.036
I succeeded.

28:24.037 --> 28:27.914
It's worse now than it was when
I started, so I changed it,

28:27.915 --> 28:30.167
being that was... This is great.

28:30.209 --> 28:31.481
It's kind of emerging.

28:31.482 --> 28:32.752
You know, it's coming.

28:32.794 --> 28:35.047
I mean, this guy, he
demands a Steadman.

28:35.088 --> 28:40.093
He really... -Something... -He
was born to have you work...

28:41.845 --> 28:44.097
I try to lighten it up a bit.

28:54.900 --> 28:56.402
The sea.

28:56.443 --> 28:59.071
The sea, where a man
can forget his trouble

28:59.112 --> 29:01.866
and the troubles of the
world, commune with something

29:01.867 --> 29:05.744
infinitely larger and more
powerful than himself.

29:07.663 --> 29:11.791
Where he could find himself
locked in an epic struggle

29:11.792 --> 29:16.004
with a creature of the sea,
plumbing the depths for that

29:11.833 --> 29:16.004
most primordial of needs:

29:16.046 --> 29:18.006
food.

29:18.048 --> 29:20.217
Well, let's hope we
have them quick.

29:51.873 --> 29:53.751
Get off, get off.

29:57.755 --> 29:59.298
Oh, my God, there's
the forehook, look.

29:59.339 --> 30:01.091
Oh, my God.

30:01.092 --> 30:02.842
Not good.

30:04.344 --> 30:06.513
Oh, my God, it got the bait.

30:07.681 --> 30:10.768
Nature, it's overrated.

30:13.520 --> 30:15.136
We're in the middle of
the English Channel.

30:15.147 --> 30:18.275
We are designed to find,
kill, tear apart,

30:18.317 --> 30:20.860
and devour the food
we need to survive.

30:20.902 --> 30:22.967
It is why God, in His
wisdom, gave us legs upon

30:22.968 --> 30:25.469
which to run, eyes in
the front of our heads

30:25.470 --> 30:27.951
to seek out prey,
fingernails and thumbs

30:27.993 --> 30:29.869
with which to tear
apart our victims,

30:29.911 --> 30:34.207
teeth to smash flesh and bone
between our mighty jaws.

30:42.591 --> 30:46.512
♪

30:50.932 --> 30:52.476
Here in the coastal
town of Weymouth

30:52.518 --> 30:54.561
at the Marlboro is
where I'll be smashing

30:54.603 --> 30:57.063
deep-fried haddock
between my freaking jaws

30:57.105 --> 30:58.940
with something called a chip.

30:58.982 --> 31:01.901
Sliced white bread and butter
so we can make a chip butty.

31:01.943 --> 31:03.069
Would you like a chip butty?

31:03.111 --> 31:05.280
I don't know that
I've ever had one.

31:05.322 --> 31:06.906
- I've heard of them.
- Delicious.

31:06.948 --> 31:08.575
All right, you're an
easy man to please.

31:08.617 --> 31:11.161
The chef suggests the mushy peas

31:11.203 --> 31:13.913
infused with butter and cream.

31:13.955 --> 31:15.367
I have such fond
memories of Weymouth.

31:15.374 --> 31:17.501
My sons went to school
just down the road.

31:17.543 --> 31:20.295
I used to bring them to the
Marlboro for lunch and that.

31:20.337 --> 31:21.963
And they weren't big
fans of fish and chips

31:22.005 --> 31:25.342
because they were, sort of, 13,
14 and they preferred meat

31:25.343 --> 31:26.552
to fish and chips.

31:26.593 --> 31:29.513
But this is the best restaurant,
in my opinion, in Weymouth.

31:29.555 --> 31:30.597
Thank you.

31:30.639 --> 31:32.932
Thank you, thank you,
that's very kind.

31:32.974 --> 31:34.518
I'll put the mushy
peas in the middle.

31:34.560 --> 31:36.353
You see, this is how
we do it in Yorkshire.

31:36.395 --> 31:38.772
So go ahead and taste the
mushy peas without vinegar.

31:38.814 --> 31:40.106
Bon appétit.

31:40.148 --> 31:41.107
They're all right.

31:41.149 --> 31:43.652
Now, put the vinegar on.

31:43.694 --> 31:48.782
Oh, my... So working-class,
as they say in Yorkshire.

31:48.824 --> 31:49.867
Mmm.

31:49.908 --> 31:50.985
Would you prefer
them with vinegar?

31:50.992 --> 31:51.986
It transforms the whole thing.

31:51.993 --> 31:54.246
Completely different, isn't it?

31:54.287 --> 31:56.874
I love buttering my bread.

31:56.915 --> 31:58.375
Now, this is the best bit.

31:58.417 --> 32:00.794
I can't believe you've
never had a chip butty.

32:00.836 --> 32:01.961
Well, today's the day.

32:02.003 --> 32:03.963
When I was a kid, this
was one of my favorites.

32:04.005 --> 32:06.966
The only fish I ever ate as
a child was fried haddock.

32:07.008 --> 32:08.968
Wouldn't eat any other fish.

32:09.010 --> 32:12.972
And then the vinegar,
quite generous.

32:13.014 --> 32:14.391
And then the salt.

32:14.433 --> 32:16.976
And this is what we call a
chip butty in Yorkshire

32:17.018 --> 32:18.395
where I come from.

32:22.482 --> 32:24.568
Mmm.

32:24.610 --> 32:27.154
I like the cheap bread
because the bread turns

32:27.155 --> 32:29.155
into the same texture
as the potato.

32:29.156 --> 32:29.989
Right.

32:30.031 --> 32:31.283
That's why it's perfect.

32:31.324 --> 32:35.141
If you have posh bread
or crusty bread, -Right.

32:35.142 --> 32:35.995
...it's not the same.

32:36.037 --> 32:38.018
How's your haddock?

32:38.019 --> 32:39.999
Good.

32:40.041 --> 32:42.419
But it's proper working-class
food, is fish and chips.

32:42.461 --> 32:45.004
Yeah, when I was a kid,
we'd eat them twice a week.

32:45.046 --> 32:47.945
They'd cook fish and chips in
dripping, -beef fat, not oil.

32:47.946 --> 32:48.842
Uh-hmm.

32:48.884 --> 32:51.678
It makes a massive, massive
difference in the flavor.

32:51.720 --> 32:54.013
Yeah.

32:54.055 --> 32:55.891
It's quite good.

32:55.933 --> 32:56.892
You were hungry.

32:56.934 --> 32:58.852
We worked hard out there.

32:58.894 --> 33:00.646
Keeping warm.

33:00.687 --> 33:02.481
Indeed.

33:02.522 --> 33:03.690
It's big.

33:03.732 --> 33:04.900
It's too big, look, I'm done.

33:04.942 --> 33:06.652
One more bite, yeah, me too.

33:06.693 --> 33:07.611
That's my problem.

33:07.653 --> 33:10.697
I go for the chip butty
before the fish.

33:12.073 --> 33:14.743
It's the child within me.

33:24.085 --> 33:26.922
Hidden away safely behind
the walls of a former

33:26.923 --> 33:29.716
Victorian-era schoolhouse,
insulated from the moronic

33:29.717 --> 33:33.052
inferno blazing outside,
is Rochelle Canteen,

33:33.094 --> 33:35.764
a green idyll, the
unpretentious brainchild

33:35.765 --> 33:38.078
of Margot Henderson and
her business partner

33:38.079 --> 33:39.058
Melanie Arnold.

33:39.100 --> 33:40.894
How long have you been
up and running here?

33:40.936 --> 33:41.708
Ten years.

33:41.709 --> 33:45.106
- God, I can't believe...
- Ten years, where have you been?

33:42.521 --> 33:45.106
I know, what is wrong with me?

33:45.148 --> 33:47.066
You were a chef
before Fergus, yes?

33:47.108 --> 33:48.902
Yeah. Well, I started
cooking in restaurants

33:48.944 --> 33:50.069
- -when I was 12.
- Yeah.

33:50.111 --> 33:52.113
But this is Fergus,
peas in their pods.

33:52.155 --> 33:54.073
We met when I was
working at the Eagle,

33:54.115 --> 33:57.160
and I said straightaway
to him, "We should open"

33:55.408 --> 33:57.160
a restaurant together."

33:57.202 --> 33:59.078
And he said, "Well,
that's a good idea",

33:59.120 --> 34:00.455
but let's be lovers as well,"

34:00.497 --> 34:02.290
which I always thought
was quite good.

34:02.332 --> 34:05.084
And then we had a restaurant.

34:05.126 --> 34:08.087
The whole area has
changed down to it.

34:08.129 --> 34:11.445
It's very Shoreditch,
groovy guys on little

34:11.446 --> 34:13.092
motorbikes with handlebars.

34:13.134 --> 34:14.379
What was the neighborhood
like before?

34:14.386 --> 34:16.513
Quite a large Bengali community.

34:16.554 --> 34:19.181
Before that, it was quite a
strong Jewish community.

34:19.224 --> 34:21.893
But then they moved out,
next group move in.

34:21.935 --> 34:23.268
It's a poor area.

34:23.311 --> 34:26.606
A lot of people working in the
fabric, clothing industries.

34:26.648 --> 34:29.525
The bandstand in the middle is
all the rubble from the war.

34:29.568 --> 34:32.152
I think the gardeners
still find, you know,

34:32.152 --> 34:34.155
children's shoes and things.

34:34.197 --> 34:35.739
Really?

34:35.741 --> 34:37.283
It is a very interesting area.

34:37.324 --> 34:40.495
Just how beautiful
these blocks are.

34:40.536 --> 34:42.288
It's quite a lot
of building works

34:42.330 --> 34:44.523
- -going on at the moment as well.
- Everywhere in London.

34:44.541 --> 34:47.543
I mean, the whole city seems
to be, kind of, transforming.

34:47.545 --> 34:51.047
It's certainly expensive...
My daughter, she's moving

34:51.089 --> 34:53.216
because of what happened
today about the EU.

34:53.257 --> 34:56.135
She's going to either live
in Scotland or New Zealand.

34:56.177 --> 35:01.140
And she's so embarrassed
and ashamed to be English.

35:01.182 --> 35:03.142
Is it the end of the world?

35:01.182 --> 35:04.978
It feels... right now, it feels
like the end of the world.

35:05.020 --> 35:06.230
We have separated.

35:06.231 --> 35:08.335
We're a little mean
island saying,

35:08.336 --> 35:10.651
"When the going gets
tough, we want to get out

35:10.652 --> 35:12.069
and just look after ourselves."

35:12.110 --> 35:15.154
It's so selfish and disgusting.

35:15.196 --> 35:18.638
It's also, out of London,
there is a lot of people

35:18.639 --> 35:20.702
who are really struggling
and have lost their way

35:20.703 --> 35:23.162
and don't believe in what
the government has done.

35:23.204 --> 35:25.164
So, I don't blame
the people either.

35:25.206 --> 35:28.167
But they're being fed, sort
of, lies, I would say.

35:28.209 --> 35:30.169
Anyway, it's all too depressing.

35:30.211 --> 35:32.672
We must change the subject.

35:32.714 --> 35:35.884
Vitello tonnato, cold-roasted
veal thinly sliced

35:35.926 --> 35:39.387
and covered with a creamy
sauce of tuna and capers.

35:39.429 --> 35:40.805
Oh, this looks good.

35:40.806 --> 35:42.181
These are good.

35:42.223 --> 35:43.224
Hmm.

35:43.225 --> 35:44.225
So, what's going right?

35:44.267 --> 35:45.978
I mean, it's a bad day to ask.

35:46.019 --> 35:47.931
Well, there's lots of great
restaurants opening in the city.

35:47.938 --> 35:49.606
Right, London, and
UK in general.

35:49.648 --> 35:51.858
It's just gotten just better
and better every year, right.

35:51.900 --> 35:52.985
It's brilliant, isn't it?

35:53.026 --> 35:54.193
It's so exciting.

35:53.026 --> 35:55.487
Great chefs... The
people who voted "for,"

35:55.528 --> 35:57.614
was it a sense of people
who feel they just...

35:57.656 --> 35:58.782
They've been screwed?

35:58.824 --> 36:00.659
I mean, young people,
unemployment in the north,

36:00.700 --> 36:01.764
it's dire.

36:01.765 --> 36:02.828
Right.

36:02.869 --> 36:04.913
People haven't got jobs.

36:04.955 --> 36:07.206
But, I mean, everyone's
looking for chefs.

36:07.248 --> 36:07.811
Right.

36:07.812 --> 36:10.877
Why we should turn... We should
set up some great big new

36:10.919 --> 36:12.211
cookery schools in Britain.

36:12.253 --> 36:14.213
I mean, no one can get
enough decent chef.

36:14.255 --> 36:16.049
- Uh-hmm.
- Some more encouragement.

36:16.091 --> 36:17.926
I mean, there is work to be had.

36:17.968 --> 36:22.221
But it's just how you find
it and where you come from.

36:22.263 --> 36:25.851
Lamb chops with lentils
and green sauce.

36:27.060 --> 36:29.062
Hmm, so good.

36:29.104 --> 36:30.264
Where'd this little
lamb come from?

36:30.271 --> 36:32.273
From Wales, Welsh lamb.

36:32.315 --> 36:35.444
Nice. People who dine out now,
do they want food simpler

36:35.445 --> 36:37.696
and more stripped down,
and with less bullshit,

36:37.737 --> 36:40.448
or do you think it's
going the other way?

36:40.490 --> 36:42.492
Simple, but with
a sort of twist.

36:42.534 --> 36:45.078
That have got a story about
where it's come from.

36:45.120 --> 36:46.454
- Right.
- It's very interesting.

36:46.496 --> 36:49.541
You know, they're all
coming up with new dishes.

36:49.582 --> 36:52.919
Should I be buying pounds now with...
No, that's what

36:52.920 --> 36:53.545
I kept thinking.

36:53.586 --> 36:54.671
What do we all do now?

36:54.713 --> 36:56.506
If I were a cruelly
cynical, exploitative...

36:56.548 --> 36:58.257
That little [indistinct]

36:58.258 --> 37:00.844
You know... what would I...
What would I be doing?

37:00.886 --> 37:02.261
Are you selling
or you're buying?

37:02.303 --> 37:03.297
Yeah, I don't... I'm [indistinct]

37:03.304 --> 37:06.058
Look at me, master
of high finance.

37:06.099 --> 37:07.184
You look so well.

37:07.225 --> 37:07.934
Well, thank you.

37:07.935 --> 37:10.269
You must be...
You're making me feel

37:08.685 --> 37:10.269
much better without them.

37:10.311 --> 37:12.355
This meal and the
wine, I have to say,

37:12.397 --> 37:15.254
your company has made me feel
much better about the world

37:15.255 --> 37:16.234
and myself.

37:26.369 --> 37:31.290
Can you reinvent yourself
in England or in London...

37:31.332 --> 37:32.500
I mean, maybe you can.

37:32.542 --> 37:33.459
I'm sure you can.

37:33.501 --> 37:35.587
But people are obsessed
with class here.

37:35.628 --> 37:36.984
Still, really?

37:36.985 --> 37:38.339
Yes, yeah, absolutely.

37:38.381 --> 37:40.299
It's our measure
of authenticity.

37:40.341 --> 37:43.095
So people are always
trying to bust people.

37:43.136 --> 37:43.824
"He's a toff!"

37:43.825 --> 37:44.512
you know.

37:44.554 --> 37:45.680
What is a toff?

37:45.722 --> 37:47.265
An aristocrat, yeah.

37:47.266 --> 37:48.808
Aristocrat? Right.

37:48.850 --> 37:52.395
My friend Adrian wrote a book
called "The Angry Isle,"

37:52.437 --> 37:54.564
and he talks about how
the British are famous

37:54.606 --> 37:59.757
for being polite, apologizing
a lot, but that that actually

37:59.758 --> 38:01.320
masks a deep anger.

38:01.362 --> 38:03.322
Do you think there's any
truth to that at all?

38:03.364 --> 38:04.734
Well, I think... because
I've been spending

38:04.741 --> 38:07.326
a lot of time in California,
which is, you know...

38:07.368 --> 38:09.061
And so when you... when
you come to London...

38:09.079 --> 38:12.249
If you come to London for
a month, you won't make

38:10.956 --> 38:13.708
any friends, and you probably
won't find anywhere to go,

38:13.750 --> 38:16.162
- but after that, the best people
- you've ever met in your life.

38:16.169 --> 38:19.422
When I went to LA, that first
month, I was so popular.

38:19.464 --> 38:22.217
Everyone's... I started,
like, six bands, and then,

38:22.218 --> 38:23.051
nothing comes of it.

38:23.093 --> 38:26.178
There's a kind of real first
impression thing... -Right

38:26.179 --> 38:28.347
...that doesn't go anywhere.

38:28.389 --> 38:30.976
In London, it's just get
it done and deal with it.

38:31.017 --> 38:32.435
Right.

38:32.477 --> 38:33.979
Well, hey!

38:34.020 --> 38:35.521
See, here we go.

38:35.563 --> 38:36.690
We're closing, closing.

38:36.691 --> 38:39.651
[indistinct] closing...
Get [indistinct] some.

38:39.692 --> 38:42.237
Staggering news is
now sinking in.

38:42.279 --> 38:44.363
Markets are giving
a brutal reaction.

38:44.405 --> 38:47.408
When the world seems like
it's spinning out of control,

38:47.450 --> 38:50.182
and the inside of your skull
feels like it's being gnawed on

38:50.183 --> 38:51.037
by angry wolverines.

38:51.079 --> 38:54.249
The sun has risen on a
completely different UK

38:54.291 --> 38:55.625
and a completely different EU.

38:55.667 --> 38:58.377
When you wake up still
tasting tequila,

38:58.419 --> 39:01.673
feeling shame, fear, and
regret in equal measures,

39:01.714 --> 39:04.530
it's good to have a friend...
Europe's weaker,

39:04.531 --> 39:07.053
Britain's divided,
where do we go now?

39:07.095 --> 39:09.848
...who, without judgment, gives
you a shoulder to cry on

39:09.889 --> 39:15.394
and maybe a simple good thing,
like some eggs and sympathy.

39:15.436 --> 39:18.190
I'm horribly and
savagely hungover.

39:18.231 --> 39:19.440
